SP  - 861
EP  - 895
VL  - 49
IS  - 5
KW  - E32
KW  - G21
KW  - J10
KW  - R21
KW  - credit constraints
KW  - house prices
KW  - home ownership
KW  - household formation
KW  - fertility
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-2879
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jmcb.12408
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We exploit regional variations in house price fluctuations in the United States during the early to mid-2000s to study the impact of the housing boom on young Americans' choices related to home ownership, household formation, and fertility. We also introduce a novel instrument for changes in house prices based on the predetermined industrial structure of the local economy. We find that in regions that experienced large increases in house prices between 2001 and 2006, the youngest households were substantially less likely to purchase residential property, to be married, and to have a child, both in 2006 and in 2011.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - What is the Economic Cost of the Investment Home Bias?
AU  - LEVY, HAIM
Y1  - 2017/08/01
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jmcb.12400
T2  - Journal of Money, Credit and Banking
JF  - Journal of Money, Credit and Banking
JO  - Journal of Money, Credit and Banking
JA  - Journal of Money, Credit and Banking
SP  - 897
EP  - 929
VL  - 49
IS  - 5
KW  - C91
KW  - D81
KW  - IHB – investment home bias
KW  - EHB – economic home bias
KW  - international diversification
KW  - correlations
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-2879
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jmcb.12400
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Overinvesting domestically is well known as an investment home bias (IHB). We define an economic home bias (EHB), whereby the IHB measures the investment weights and the EHB measures the economic cost induced by the IHB. We may have a large IHB and a negligible EHB. With the increase in the average correlation between foreign markets from 0.4 for the decade ending in 1988 to about 0.9 for more recent decades, the U.S. EHB is becoming negligible despite the domestic investment of 77.5%. Since 2009, the correlations have decreased, indicating that the HB puzzle is emerging once again.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Nowcasting U.S. Headline and Core Inflation
AU  - KNOTEK II, EDWARD S.
AU  - ZAMAN, SAEED
